# Frontend wireframe conventions

Treat every UI task in this project as **prototype-first implementation**: prioritize clarity, consistency, and clickable flows over production-grade architecture.  

When generating screens, aim to **replicate the existing UI language** (layout rhythm, spacing, typography, component patterns, and navigation behavior) so new work feels like a natural extension of what is already present. If the codebase has little UI yet, establish a **minimal consistent shell** using this rule instead of inventing a new style per screen.

Before coding, quickly infer and follow the current conventions for:

- how routes/screens are organized,
- how reusable components are composed,
- how interactions are represented in demos (stubs, placeholders, simple state),
- and how styling choices communicate hierarchy over polish.

If something is ambiguous, prefer the **simplest believable wireframe behavior** and leave a short note indicating it is provisional for design feedback.

## Structure

- Organize by **user journey** (routes or top-level sections), not by maximal component abstraction.
- One screen = one primary intent; avoid nesting many unrelated states in a single view unless the demo/mock of the user's journey requires it.

## Components

- Reuse a **small** set of layout primitives (page shell, section, stack) before extracting deep abstractions.
- Duplication is acceptable if it keeps the prototype **easy to read and delete** when design changes.

## Interactions

- Every critical path should be **clickable** end-to-end, even if actions only show a toast, modal, or “success” stub.
- Loading and empty states: use **simple placeholders** (skeleton blocks, one line of copy) so flows feel real in demos.

## Styling

- **All UI colors must use the [Flexoki](https://stephango.com/flexoki) palette**—semantic base tokens and accent ramps only. Do not introduce arbitrary hex/RGB/HSL values outside Flexoki (including “close enough” grays).
- **Name tokens like Flexoki’s UI roles** so implementation stays aligned with the system.
- **Light vs dark:** follow Flexoki’s documented mappings (e.g. light UI: accent **600** weights for emphasized accent UI; dark UI: accent **400** weights where Flexoki specifies). Prefer the **base/paper ramp** for wireframe chrome (warm paper-like backgrounds, ink-like text and grays) so the prototype stays high-contrast and legible without breaking out of the system.
- **Wireframe discipline:** achieve a “mostly neutral” wireframe look by leaning on the Flexoki **base** ramp for surfaces and borders; use accents **sparingly** for links, focus rings, validation, and clear semantic states (success/error/warning).
- Centralize color, typography and other styling choices so that it's easy to tweak the project globally.
